   "content": [
      {
         "id": "SECTION_prerequisites",
         "text": [
            {
               "text": "<p><span id=\"htZoomImageMsg\"></span></p>",
               "source": null,
               "date_time": null,
               "isTable": false,
               "imgdesc": "",
               "format": "html",
               "PostMention": ""
            },
            {
               "text": "<p><h3>Prerequisites</h3>In this text, we explore how the human body served as the basis for numerical systems. For more details, we recommend starting with:</p><p><ul><li><a href=\"#\" onclick=\"htCleanSources(); htFillReferenceSource('9618a83e-f232-49db-84f6-fc3455a3f1d1'); return false;\">Drawing to count</a>: show how we change from our fingers to geometric pictures.</li><li><a href=\"#\" onclick=\"htCleanSources(); htFillReferenceSource('00f3ab60-2017-420a-99dc-56de384243e8'); return false;\">Numerical families</a>: Illustrating the relationship between our ancestors and numbers.</li></ul></p>",
               "source": null,
               "date_time": null,
               "isTable": false,
               "imgdesc": "",
               "format": "html",
               "PostMention": ""
            }
         ]
      },
      {
         "id": "SECTION_introduction",
         "text": [
            {
               "text": "<p><h3>Growth in indigenous cultures</h3>When we think of growth, the first association is often with physical height. Among indigenous peoples, growth can be observed in various aspects of their cultures, including sacred landscapes and numerical systems.</p>",
               "source": null,
               "date_time": null,
               "isTable": false,
               "imgdesc": "",
               "format": "html",
               "PostMention": ""
            }
         ]
      },
      {
         "id": "SECTION_mountain",
         "text": [
            {
               "text": "<p><h3>Sacred mountains</h3>In Mesoamerican archaeological sites, sacred mountains hold significant cultural importance (<a href=\"#\" onclick=\"htCleanSources(); htFillReferenceSource('960e3a8e-3a60-4ee4-9df4-e2187489e3b9'); return false;\">García Capistrán, H., <htdate0>, pp. 144</a>). These mountains have also \"grown\" over time. For instance, consider Temple 16 in Copán, Honduras:</p><p class=\"desc\"><img id=\"imgCopanTemple\" onclick=\"htImageZoom('imgCopanTemple', '0%')\" src=\"images/Copan/Temple16Copan.png\" class=\"imgcenter\"/><b>Figure 1</b>: Poster at the Copán archaeological site (<a href=\"#\" onclick=\"htCleanSources(); htFillReferenceSource('1e007481-9bd3-4a09-ad4d-6e812fe79641'); return false;\">Instituto Hondureño de Antropologia e Historia, <htdate1></a>). Photo taken on <htdate2>, during a visit to the site.</p>",
               "source": null,
               "date_time": [
                  {
                     "type": "gregory",
                     "year": "2018",
                     "month": "-1",
                     "day": "-1"
                  },
                  {
                     "type": "gregory",
                     "year": "2024",
                     "month": "-1",
                     "day": "-1"
                  },
                  {
                     "type": "gregory",
                     "year": "2015",
                     "month": "7",
                     "day": "30"
                  }
               ],
               "isTable": false,
               "imgdesc": "This panel shows the 9 building steps of the Temple 16 in Copan. We can observe after the three small building steps, the fourth step is a big basis for the next steps. Among all steps, it is highlighted the Rosalila, with their multiple entrances and an space on top for somebody communicate with population.",
               "format": "html",
               "PostMention": ""
            },
            {
               "text": "<p>In <b>Figure 1</b>, you can observe the different phases of construction before Temple 16 was completed. For more detailed information on these reconstructions, Luiz Tuarez's work offers a thorough exploration (<a href=\"#\" onclick=\"htCleanSources(); htFillReferenceSource('daae87a2-5fa9-43d1-88fb-6713b25d50d5'); return false;\">Tuarez Mejia, L. F., <htdate0>, pp. 120 - 128</a>). </p>",
               "source": null,
               "date_time": [
                  {
                     "type": "gregory",
                     "year": "2023",
                     "month": "-1",
                     "day": "-1"
                  }
               ],
               "isTable": false,
               "imgdesc": "",
               "format": "html",
               "PostMention": ""
            }
         ]
      },
      {
         "id": "SECTION_mesoamerica",
         "text": [
            {
               "text": "<p><h3>Mesoamerican numerical numbers</h3>The Mesoamerican numerical system is vigesimal (<a href=\"#\" onclick=\"htCleanSources(); htFillReferenceSource('ad11b3b2-8cdf-4d71-9cb7-2ac241850945'); return false;\">Casares Contreras, Orlando & Cetina, José & Cabrera, Venus Sarahí, <htdate0>, pp. 26 - 29 (ResearchGate)</a> ; <a href=\"#\" onclick=\"htCleanSources(); htFillReferenceSource('eca99877-c520-4569-a71c-0a5b3dd77dc4'); return false;\">Casares Contreras, Orlando & Cetina, José & Cabrera, Venus Sarahí, <htdate1>, pp. 26 - 29 (Revista)</a> ; <a href=\"#\" onclick=\"htCleanSources(); htFillReferenceSource('ceffba8a-43be-4de3-a5c8-27cdf81311b1'); return false;\">Puente, Francisco Barriga, <htdate2>, pp. 32, 34</a> ; <a href=\"#\" onclick=\"htCleanSources(); htFillReferenceSource('ced67eaf-7378-4589-9166-07f799969e3e'); return false;\">Catepillán, Ximena, <htdate3></a>), meaning it is based on 20 different symbols. Progressing to the next \"generation\" of numbers occurs after reaching 19 (<a href=\"#\" onclick=\"htCleanSources(); htFillReferenceSource('00f3ab60-2017-420a-99dc-56de384243e8'); return false;\">History Traces, <htdate4>, Famílias numéricas</a>). When this limit is reached, the number resets to zero, and one unit is added to the next place value. The figure below illustrates the indigenous representation of numbers from 0 to 99:</p><p><table class=\"mesoamerican\"><tr><th>Mesoamerican number</th><th>Decimal numbers</th><th>Controls</th></tr> <tr><td><img onclick=\"htImageZoom('tmc1l1', '0%')\" src=\"\" id=\"tmc1l1\" /></td><td id=\"tmc2l1\" rowspan=\"2\"><span class=\"text_to_paint\" id=\"mesoIndoArabic\">0</span></td><td><i class=\"fa-solid fa-caret-up upArrowWithFA\" name=\"mesoUp\"></i></td></tr> <tr><td><img  onclick=\"htImageZoom('tmc1l2', '0%')\" src=\"\" id=\"tmc1l2\" /></td><td><i class=\"fa-solid fa-caret-down downArrowWithFA\" name=\"mesoDown\"></i></td></tr></table></p>",
               "source": null,
               "date_time": [
                  {
                     "type": "gregory",
                     "year": "2022",
                     "month": "-1",
                     "day": "-1"
                  },
                  {
                     "type": "gregory",
                     "year": "2022",
                     "month": "-1",
                     "day": "-1"
